<a class='sd-link-color'></a></div></div>\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-content -->\n\t\n\t<div class=\"entry-links\">\n\t\t<p class=\"comment-number\"><a href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/2014/01/02/the-best-headphone-songs-of-2013-2/#comments\" title=\"Comment on The Best Headphone Songs of&nbsp;2013\">1 Comment</a></p>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t<p class=\"entry-categories tagged\">Filed under <a href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/category/music-2/\" title=\"View all posts in Music\" rel=\"category tag\">Music</a>, <a href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/category/personal/\" title=\"View all posts in Personal\" rel=\"category tag\">Personal</a></p>\n\t\t\t<p class=\"entry-tags tagged\">Tagged as <a href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/tag/dan-deacon/\" rel=\"tag\">dan deacon</a>, <a href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/tag/headphones/\" rel=\"tag\">headphones</a>, <a href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/tag/james-blake/\" rel=\"tag\">James Blake</a>, <a href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/tag/kanye-west/\" rel=\"tag\">Kanye West</a>, <a href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/tag/listicles/\" rel=\"tag\">listicles</a>, <a href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/tag/music/\" rel=\"tag\">music</a>, <a href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/tag/music-videos/\" rel=\"tag\">music videos</a>, <a href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/tag/soundcloud/\" rel=\"tag\">soundcloud</a><br /></p>\n\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-links -->\n\n</div><!-- #post-## -->\n\n\n\n<div id=\"post-7227\" class=\"post-7227 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-pictures-2 category-travel-2 tag-madeira tag-portugal\">\n\t<div class=\"entry-meta\">\n\n\t\tJanuary 1, 2014 &middot; 9:24 am\t</div><!-- .entry-meta -->\n\n\t<h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/2014/01/01/madeira/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Things I&#8217;ll Never&nbsp;Understand</a></h2>\t<div class=\"entry entry-content\">\n\t\t<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7231\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2014/01/img_3337.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7231\" alt=\"IMG_3337\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2014/01/img_3337.jpg?w=500&#038;h=344\" width=\"500\" height=\"344\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">One of the reasons I think Iâ€™m not ready to have kids is that I wouldnâ€™t be able to answer their questions about life basics.</dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7235\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2014/01/img_3902.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7235\" alt=\"IMG_3902\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2014/01/img_3902.jpg?w=500&#038;h=375\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">Why is the sky blue, where do mountains come from, etc.</dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7233\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2014/01/img_3412.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7233\" alt=\"IMG_3412\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2014/01/img_3412.jpg?w=500&#038;h=375\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">I donâ€™t know why I know so little about this stuff. I went to high school, college, grad school (twice!). I have read books, sometimes even for fun.</dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7228\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2014/01/img_3270.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7228\" alt=\"IMG_3270\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2014/01/img_3270.jpg?w=500&#038;h=666\" width=\"500\" height=\"666\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">But when confronted with nature, the real kind, still and un-narrated, I canâ€™t explain any of the whys or hows.</dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7225\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3531.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7225\" alt=\"IMG_3531\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3531.jpg?w=500&#038;h=375\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">I spent Christmas this year in Madeira.</dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7224\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3502.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7224\" alt=\"IMG_3502\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3502.jpg?w=500&#038;h=666\" width=\"500\" height=\"666\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">It&#8217;s island off the coast of Morocco that, for random historical reasons, is an autonomous region of Portugal, like a little European Hawaii.</dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7222\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3452.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7222\" alt=\"IMG_3452\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3452.jpg?w=500&#038;h=375\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">I knew very little about it before I visited. But now, because I have been there, I am interested in it.</dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7221\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3430.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7221\" alt=\"IMG_3430\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3430.jpg?w=500&#038;h=375\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">It was discovered in the early 1400s, uninhabited, a spike of volcano that wriggled up out of the Atlantic, then spend the next 5 million years getting ground back down to sea level.</dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7220\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3981.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7220\" alt=\"IMG_3981\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3981.jpg?w=500&#038;h=375\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">This process is apparently ongoing. Most of what&#8217;s sticking out of the water is hills. The old joke among the locals is &#8216;The only flat surfaces on Madeira are vertical.&#8217;</dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7241\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2014/01/img_3306.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7241\" alt=\"IMG_3306\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2014/01/img_3306.jpg?w=500&#038;h=666\" width=\"500\" height=\"666\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">The climate is perfect for growing sugarcane, so the early years were spent terracing the hills, creating stairstep cropland, cultivating it one stripe at a time. All the agriculture is still done by hand.Â </dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7218\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3970.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7218\" alt=\"IMG_3970\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3970.jpg?w=500&#038;h=375\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">Sugar crashed when Europe discovered Brazil, the Caribbean, slavery. Madeira converted its little sugar plots into little vineyards.Â </dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7216\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3962.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7216\" alt=\"IMG_3962\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3962.jpg?w=500&#038;h=666\" width=\"500\" height=\"666\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">That worked til the 1890s, when a disease wiped out all the grapes (think Irish potato famine, but this time the victims were warm-weather alcoholics).Â </dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7212\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3859.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7212\" alt=\"IMG_3859\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3859.jpg?w=500&#038;h=598\" width=\"500\" height=\"598\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">The economy crashed, most of the island emigrated.</dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7211\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3349.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7211 \" alt=\"IMG_3349\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3349.jpg?w=500&#038;h=375\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">Nowadays they still grow cropsâ€”those are banana trees down thereâ€”but mostly they cultivate tourists, people like me who fly all the way here for the weather and the pictures and the differences.</dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7210\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3825.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7210\" alt=\"IMG_3825\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3825.jpg?w=500&#038;h=666\" width=\"500\" height=\"666\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">This narrative, the path Madeira took Â here, it makes sense to me, itâ€™s full of people and businesses and a big economy that goes boom one century and pfffft the next.Â </dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7208\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3819.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7208\" alt=\"IMG_3819\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3819.jpg?w=500&#038;h=375\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">That&#8217;s the story of everywhere, basically.</dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7204\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3801.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7204\" alt=\"IMG_3801\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3801.jpg?w=500&#038;h=375\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">But then I bike to the top of a mountain on this very same boom-and-pffft island and I am holding my boyfriendâ€™s hand and we are looking together at a bunch of lava rocks sticking out through a beach and I realize that I have no idea why some rocks get ground into sand and others donâ€™t.</dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7203\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3796.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7203\" alt=\"IMG_3796\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3796.jpg?w=500&#038;h=375\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">And then Iâ€™m thinking that if I was at the top of this same mountain, holding my sonâ€™s hand instead of my boyfriendâ€™s, this is the shit he would ask me about, the rocks and the sun and why is the water that shade of blue and how many stars are there in the sky and I have no idea how to answer.</dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7200\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3665.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7200\" alt=\"IMG_3665\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3665.jpg?w=500&#038;h=375\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">Or maybe he wonâ€™t ask me, maybe weâ€™re not the kind of society where we do that anymore. Maybe heâ€™ll stand on that mountain and look at that beach and use his free hand to whip out his little tablet or whatever and heâ€™ll read the Wikipedia entry about lava and we&#8217;ll stand there and neither of us will say anything.</dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7199\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3615.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7199\" alt=\"IMG_3615\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3615.jpg?w=500&#038;h=375\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">And maybe that&#8217;s better for both of us. I can&#8217;t explain how anything works when it&#8217;s really small or really big or made of rocks, when it can&#8217;t tell me how it works itself.</dd>\n</dl>\n<dl class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_7202\" style=\"width:510px;\">\n<dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3780.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-7202\" alt=\"IMG_3780\" src=\"https://rottenindenmark.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/img_3780.jpg?w=500&#038;h=666\" width=\"500\" height=\"666\" /></a></dt>\n<dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">But hey, if he ever wants to know how the islandâ€™s GDP is calculated, I&#8217;m right next to him.</dd>\n</dl>\n<div id=\"jp-post-flair\" class=\"sharedaddy sd-like-enabled sd-sharing-enabled\"><div class=\"sharedaddy sd-sharing-enabled\"><div class=\"robots-nocontent sd-block sd-social sd-social-icon-text sd-sharing\"><h3 class=\"sd-title\">Share this:</h3><div class=\"sd-content\"><ul><li class=\"share-facebook\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"share-facebook sd-button share-icon\" href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/2014/01/01/madeira/?share=facebook\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Share on Facebook\" id=\"sharing-facebook-7227\"><span>Facebook</span></a></li><li class=\"share-twitter\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"share-twitter sd-button share-icon\" href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/2014/01/01/madeira/?share=twitter\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Click to share on Twitter\" id=\"sharing-twitter-7227\"><span>Twitter</span></a></li><li class=\"share-tumblr\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"share-tumblr sd-button share-icon\" href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/2014/01/01/madeira/?share=tumblr\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Click to share on Tumblr\"><span>Tumblr</span></a></li><li class=\"share-reddit\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"share-reddit sd-button share-icon\" href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/2014/01/01/madeira/?share=reddit\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Click to share on Reddit\"><span>Reddit</span></a></li><li class=\"share-stumbleupon\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"share-stumbleupon sd-button share-icon\" href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/2014/01/01/madeira/?share=stumbleupon\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Click to share on StumbleUpon\"><span>StumbleUpon</span></a></li><li class=\"share-email\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"share-email sd-button share-icon\" href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/2014/01/01/madeira/?share=email\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Click to email this to a friend\"><span>Email</span></a></li><li><a href=\"#\" class=\"sharing-anchor sd-button share-more\"><span>More</span></a></li><li class=\"share-end\"></li></ul><div class=\"sharing-hidden\"><div class=\"inner\" style=\"display: none;\"><ul><li class=\"share-google-plus-1\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"share-google-plus-1 sd-button share-icon\" href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/2014/01/01/madeira/?share=google-plus-1\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Click to share on Google+\" id=\"sharing-google-7227\"><span>Google</span></a></li><li class=\"share-digg\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"share-digg sd-button share-icon\" href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/2014/01/01/madeira/?share=digg\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Click to Digg this post\"><span>Digg</span></a></li><li class=\"share-end\"></li><li class=\"share-print\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"share-print sd-button share-icon\" href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/2014/01/01/madeira/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Click to print\"><span>Print</span></a></li><li class=\"share-linkedin\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"share-linkedin sd-button share-icon\" href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/2014/01/01/madeira/?share=linkedin\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Click to share on LinkedIn\" id=\"sharing-linkedin-7227\"><span>LinkedIn</span></a></li><li class=\"share-end\"></li><li class=\"share-end\"></li></ul></div></div></div></div></div><div class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-15624535-7227-52f48117da645' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/#blog_id=15624535&amp;post_id=7227&amp;origin=rottenindenmark.wordpress.com&amp;obj_id=15624535-7227-52f48117da645' data-name='like-post-frame-15624535-7227-52f48117da645'><h3 class='sd-title'>Like this:</h3><div class='likes-widget-placeholder post-likes-widget-placeholder' style='height:55px'><span class='button'><span>Like</span></span> <span class=\"loading\">Loading...</span></div><span class='sd-text-color'></span><a class='sd-link-color'></a></div></div>\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-content -->\n\t\n\t<div class=\"entry-links\">\n\t\t<p class=\"comment-number\"><a href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/2014/01/01/madeira/#comments\" title=\"Comment on Things I&#8217;ll Never&nbsp;Understand\">12 Comments</a></p>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t<p class=\"entry-categories tagged\">Filed under <a href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/category/pictures-2/\" title=\"View all posts in Pictures\" rel=\"category tag\">Pictures</a>, <a href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/category/travel-2/\" title=\"View all posts in Travel\" rel=\"category tag\">Travel</a></p>\n\t\t\t<p class=\"entry-tags tagged\">Tagged as <a href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/tag/madeira/\" rel=\"tag\">madeira</a>, <a href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/tag/portugal/\" rel=\"tag\">portugal</a><br /></p>\n\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-links -->\n\n</div><!-- #post-## -->\n\n\n\n<div id=\"post-7185\" class=\"post-7185 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-essays-2 category-london-2 category-personal category-work-2\">\n\t<div class=\"entry-meta\">\n\n\t\tDecember 20, 2013 &middot; 8:08 am\t</div><!-- .entry-meta -->\n\n\t<h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/2013/12/20/what-happens-when-one-of-your-coworkers-dies/\" rel=\"bookmark\">What Happens When One of Your Coworkers&nbsp;Dies</a></h2>\t<div class=\"entry entry-content\">\n\t\t<p><em>Originally posted on <a href=\"http://thebillfold.com/2013/12/what-happens-when-one-of-your-coworkers-dies/\">The Billfold</a></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The first thing that happens is someone tells you.</p>\n<p>Itâ€™s Tuesday, itâ€™s February, itâ€™s my first day back at work after a week on vacation. I notice the candle in the foyer just as the whoosh of the door blows it out.Â <em>They never did that forÂ </em>my<em>Â birthday</em>, I think as I walk past reception.</p>\n<p>This is my job. Itâ€™s a publisher, we make coffee table books about movies, architecture, political issues that lend themselves to stock photography. Most of us think of ourselves as writers, though that is not really what we do anymore.</p>\n<p>Dominic is the one who tells me. He and Naomi are here already, sitting at opposite desks, leaning in like theyâ€™re playing Battleship. Dominic bikes here from some distant suburb Iâ€™ve never heard of, then showers and changes into the same thing every day: pressed white shirt, pastel v-neck, khakis, loafers. Iâ€™ve never been here early enough to see what heâ€™s wearing when he arrives.</p>\n<p>â€œHey there Mike,â€ he says. His Dutch accent sharpens the thâ€™s into dâ€™s.Â <em>Hey der.Â </em>He turns off his monitor and swivels toward me.</p>\n<p>Naomi looks up, holding a mug dangling two teabag strings. She moved here three months ago from Australia, she still has that new-hire enthusiasm, the â€œletâ€™s make great books!â€ gusto weâ€™re all waiting to wear off.</p>\n<p>â€œWell hello, Mike!â€ she says as I de-layer at my deskâ€”hat, scarf, glovesâ€”and turn my computer on.</p>\n<p>Sheâ€™s about to say something else, but Dominic gives a little traffic-cop hand wave and she stops.</p>\n<p>â€œMike donâ€™t open your e-mails,â€ he says.</p>\n<p>Thatâ€™s when I notice that our office has a candle in it too.</p>\n<p>â€œYou need to know,â€ he says, trails off, starts again, â€œthat Colin has passed away.â€</p>\n<p>â€œColin in marketing?â€</p>\n<p>â€œCorrect.â€</p>\n<p>Colin Schwartz. The guy at the back of the external-relations office, a sliver between two big iMac screens.</p>\n<p>â€œOh fuck,â€ I say. â€œHow?â€</p>\n<p>Last Monday, Dominic says, Colin didnâ€™t show up to work and didnâ€™t call or e-mail to explain where he was. On Tuesday his boss told HR. On Thursday the office manager went to his apartment to see if he was home. No one answered her knock. She called the police. They forced open the door and found his body.</p>\n<p>â€œOh fuck,â€ I say again. â€œWas it like a heart attack or something?â€</p>\n<p>â€œWell, as you may know, Colin was depressed,â€ Dominic says. â€œHe had some emotional problems. So it looks likeâ€¦â€</p>\n<p>â€œOhÂ <em>fuck</em>,â€ I say. â€œAre you saying he killed himself?â€</p>\n<p>â€œNothingâ€™s clear right now.â€</p>\n<p>â€œThey had a meeting yesterday and the MD told us,â€ Naomi says. â€œEveryone in marketing went home.â€</p>\n<p>I stare at my keyboard for a second, type in my password, open Outlook. Thereâ€™s the official announcement from our president, the meeting cancellations, the invite from comms to record memories of Colin.</p>\n<p>â€œOK Mike,â€ Dominic says, and swivels back to his desk.</p>\n<p>â€œSo, um,â€ Naomi says, â€œhow was your vacation?â€</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">&#8212;</p>\n<p>The next thing that happens is we are terrible.</p>\n<p>â€œI donâ€™t want to say I saw it coming or anything, but itâ€™s not exactly out of the blue,â€ says Bill, who runs our Twitter feed.</p>\n<p>The roof of our building is the size of a soccer field, but weâ€™re bunched together by the door, hoods up, facing away from the wind. Bill is the only one smoking out here, the rest of us are just listening.</p>\n<p>â€œThey were working him too hard,â€ says Will, one of the copy editors. â€œMarketingâ€™s way understaffed.â€</p>\n<p>I barely knew Colin. He sat two offices down from me, but we never worked on anything together, never laid eyes on each other after 5 p.m. Our relationship consisted, in its entirety, of work-related small talk in the break room, his lunch rotating behind us in the microwave. Ding, stir, have a good rest of your day.</p>\n<p>After Dominic told me, I spent an hour thinking things like,Â <em>Was it something I did? Could I have reached out to him?Â </em>Then I spent at least twice that long thinking,Â <em>Of course not, asshole</em>.</p>\n<p>â€œI was on a conference call with Colin two weeks ago. He stopped talking in the middle of a sentence and just started breathing really loud,â€ Bill says.</p>\n<p>Iâ€™ve been having conversations like this all over the building. Itâ€™s Wednesday, itâ€™s right after lunch, itâ€™s been two days since they announced Colin died. And this is how weâ€™ve spent it: Bunched up in corners, whispering things to see if they are true.</p>\n<p>Sarah from finance wonders if Colinâ€™s death has anything to do with the department restructuring. Mark in HR heard Colin didnâ€™t take a vacation for the last two years. Tina from photos heard Colin moved here to study at the London School of Economics, but dropped out.</p>\n<p>None of these people knew Colin any better than I did. Weâ€™re just magnifying what we know, zooming in on the crumbs as if it will reveal where they lead.</p>\n<p>â€œYou know they changed his job title without consulting him.â€ Bill says, and the rest of us nod solemnly.</p>\n<p>I wish I could say I was the grown-up here, the one who pointed out that none of us really knew Colin, that his death was none of our business, that we should all get back to work. But I wasnâ€™t.</p>\n<p>â€œHe was gay,â€ I say. I only found this out yesterday, when Dominic mentioned Colinâ€™s boyfriend had been notified. â€œDo you think that has anything to do with it?â€</p>\n<p>â€œThe weird thing is, Colin never struck me as the unhappiest person here,â€ says Jessica, the receptionist. â€œI would have put Colin way down the list. Like, look at Chris in Online. That guy puts in earbuds when he walks to the bathroom.â€</p>\n<p>â€œI saw Lucy talking to the external relations director yesterday,â€ Will says. â€œI think sheâ€™s applying for his job.â€</p>\n<p>â€œOh shit I hope itâ€™s not her,â€ Bill says. â€œRemember that presentation she gave at the annual meeting last year?â€ I smirk along with everyone else. Bill lights another cigarette, giving us all permission to stay out here at least five more minutes.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">&#8212;</p>\n<p>The next thing that happens is we mourn.</p>\n<p>Itâ€™s Thursday, itâ€™s 10 a.m., itâ€™s our weekly staff meeting. Colinâ€™s picture is projected on the wall. The senior management team is sitting in suits at the big conference table, each with their own box of tissues.</p>\n<p>Iâ€™m leaning against the wall. Thereâ€™s only room in here for about 50 chairs, most of us are standing. Naomi is in sitting down next to me, sheâ€™s already crying.</p>\n<p>The managing director starts talking, the only voice in the room. He tells us how this is going to work. For the last two days, comms has been recording employees talking about Colin, how they want to remember him. Today weâ€™re going to watch the video.</p>\n<p>â€œThe speculation has to stop,â€ he says. â€œColin died of natural causes.â€</p>\n<p>He nods over to the comms director, who hits play. The video begins with Colinâ€™s workâ€”excerpts of promos he made, books he launched, conference presentations he gaveâ€”then the rest is testimonials from his colleagues. Theyâ€™re edited together in reverse hierarchical order.</p>\n<p>Interns, then assistants, then peers, describe working with Colin. The time they bumped into him at the printer, the time his soup exploded in the microwave, the time they sat together on a bus from the airport to a conference, each with their headphones on.</p>\n<p>Story after story, theyâ€™re all like this, proximity aspiring to intimacy, and itâ€™s clear that no one here knew him, not the people in his department, not his managers, not the people he had lunch with and traveled with. They talk about his cluttered desk, his e-mail forwards, his cocktails at the Christmas party. They try to pull a person out of the time he spent here and they canâ€™t.</p>\n<p>â€œI always said hi to Colin when I passed him in the hall,â€ says someone on the video.</p>\n<p>Naomi stops crying. She makes a little sound like sheâ€™s surprised, like sheâ€™s discovered the exact borders of her compassion. She takes a shallow breath, puts her purse on her lap, starts looking through it for tissues.</p>\n<p>Colinâ€™s boss is on vacation this week. He recorded a message by webcam. Heâ€™s lying on his side on a hotel bed. He talks about the clarity of Colinâ€™s press releases as palm trees shudder in the wind behind him.</p>\n<p>â€œI wish I had gotten to know him better,â€ he says. â€œHe seemed nice.â€</p>\n<p>That comment, those three words, and I jerk my head away from the screen. I look out the window and there is a huge piece of bird shit on the windowsill. People on the screen keep talking, managers and directors now, but their memories of him are all the same hellos and bump-intos and chit-chats, and I realize this is it, this is what he left behind, his lunch and his e-mails and the clever thing he wrote on his bossâ€™s birthday card. I close my eyes and the video goes on and on and then I open them and everyone around me is crying.</p>\n<p>The last clip is the MD, chest heaving. Heâ€™s telling the camera, us, how Colin prepped him for his first TV interview.</p>\n<p>â€œDonâ€™t gesture so much,â€ Colin told him, â€œGesturing looks awkward on TV. Emphasize with your words, not your hands.â€</p>\n<p>The MD did his interview, a whole hour, with his hands in his lap, as instructed. And afterwards he asked Colin, â€œhow did I do?â€ and Colin said â€œYou were like a statue up there! Why didnâ€™t you use your hands?!â€</p>\n<p>And we all laugh, and the camera stays pointed at the MD, and his smile fades, his eyes go wet, he lets out a sob and the camera turns off and the screen shows Colinâ€™s picture again.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">&#8212;</p>\n<p>The next thing that happens is it makes us close.</p>\n<p>After the staff meeting, we shut the door to our office and Naomi asks me if I knew anyone else who died. I tell her about my godmother who got brain cancer when I was 12.</p>\n<p>â€œDid you know her well?â€ she asks.</p>\n<p>â€œIn whatever way kids know adults, I guess. We spent a lot of time together when I was little. I mostly remember her mac and cheese.â€</p>\n<p>Then I ask Naomi and she tells me about the principal of her Catholic school who died in a car accident when she was seven. It was her first funeral, and she raised his hand in the middle of the eulogy to ask a question. As sheâ€™s telling it she lets herself smile a little, and I realize I never knew she went to Catholic school.</p>\n<p>Itâ€™s like this the rest of the week. Maybe itâ€™s because the MD asked us to stop speculating, or maybe everyone else saw the video like I did, felt the same urgency to populate this place, but we stop talking about Colin and we start talking about us.</p>\n<p>On the roof, Bill tells me that his parents died when he was 22. He had just finished his first triathlon, and was so tired he fell asleep on the note his roommate had left on his bed. He woke up, pulled it out from under the covers and read it, still in his little running shorts.</p>\n<p>In the break room, Jessica is hanging up a picture of Colin. She tells me that when she was 10 years old she accidentally took a big handful of childrenâ€™s Tylenol because it was flavored and she thought it was candy.</p>\n<p>â€œFor years, my parents thought it was a suicide attempt,â€ she says, yanking out a strip of scotch tape.</p>\n<p>On Friday Dominic and I walk to the train station together and he tells me about the cat he buried in his backyard when he was seven.</p>\n<p>â€œI dug him up two years ago,â€™ he says, â€œand he was just a box of bones.â€™ He makes two fists, huge in his mittens, to show me his size.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">&#8212;</p>\n<p>The next thing that happens is itâ€™s all over.</p>\n<p>Monday morning, in the corridor past reception, I walk past marketing and hear someone say. â€œDid you see Jessica crying at the staff meeting? She barely even knew him.â€</p>\n<p>Dominic is already here, and I wonder if his khakis, his pianist posture, are the things I would say about him if he died.</p>\n<p>â€œDid Naomi send the invite last week for the meeting with research?â€ he says.</p>\n<p>â€œI donâ€™t think so,â€ I say. â€œWith everything happening last week, she must have forgotten.â€</p>\n<p>â€œWell if people are going to be here,â€ he says, â€œthey might as well be working.â€</p>\n<p>Itâ€™s not that we forget, itâ€™s just that weâ€™re done remembering together. As the memorial fades from memory, as the tasks pile up and dwindle, as we all settle back into our boxes on the org chart, our dead colleague becomes just another thing we think about but donâ€™t say.</p>\n<p>The last time we talk about Colin at work is in a budget meeting. Itâ€™s March, itâ€™s six weeks since Colin died, itâ€™s me and Dominic in a conference room with Marketing, getting an overview of our spending before the quarterly board meeting.</p>\n<p>â€œWhatâ€™s this 40,000 that appeared in the budget in February?â€ Dominic asks.</p>\n<p>â€œThatâ€™s Colin,â€ says Bill. Dead people donâ€™t get salaries, so Colinâ€™s appears as a surplus.</p>\n<p>â€œOK,â€ Dominic says. â€œAnd why has this travel spending figure been adjusted?â€</p>\n<p>And thatâ€™s it, we just move through the rest of the budget. I think about looking up, making eye contact across the table, sharing an acknowledgement of the moment that just passed. Instead, I just keep my eyes on the Excel sheet, keep following the numbers with my pencil.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">&#8212;</p>\n<p>The last thing that happens is Naomi quits.</p>\n<p>â€œIâ€™m going back to my old job in Adelaide,â€ she says. Itâ€™s April, itâ€™s Friday, itâ€™s two months since Colin died. Weâ€™re sitting on the stoop of a church near work, holding paper coffee cups with two hands, watching rain drip from the awning.</p>\n<p>â€œWhy?â€ I ask.</p>\n<p>â€œDo you remember Colin?â€ she says.</p>\n<p>I tell her I barely knew him.</p>\n<p>â€œNeither did I,â€ she says. â€œBut do you remember the week after he died?â€</p>\n<p>We talk about the memorial, everyone crying, how we were with each other afterwards, how weâ€™re not anymore.</p>\n<p>â€œI keep making these pledges to get to know people here,â€ she says, â€œand then in the very next second I know that Iâ€™m not going to, that itâ€™s too hard. At least back in Australia I have family waiting for me at the end of the day.â€</p>\n<p>I feel like we should hug now but we donâ€™t. I stand up, take the empty coffee cup out of Naomiâ€™s hand, throw it in the trash.</p>\n<p>Itâ€™s later, itâ€™s after Naomi left, itâ€™s me and Dominic in the break room, his lunch rotating in the microwave. Heâ€™s looking at the picture of Colin posted on the wall.</p>\n<p>â€œItâ€™s too close to the microwave,â€ he says. â€œThe steam is going to make it come down.â€</p>\n<p>As if agreeing, the microwave dings.</p>\n<p>â€œHere,â€ he says.</p>\n<p>He leans in, grabs it from the wall, moves it higher, sticks it back to the wall. â€œThatâ€™s better.â€</p>\n<p>He grabs his soup from the microwave, stirs it.</p>\n<p>â€œOK Mike,â€ he says. â€œHave a good rest of your day.â€</p>\n<div id=\"jp-post-flair\" class=\"sharedaddy sd-like-enabled sd-sharing-enabled\"><div class=\"sharedaddy sd-sharing-enabled\"><div class=\"robots-nocontent sd-block sd-social sd-social-icon-text sd-sharing\"><h3 class=\"sd-title\">Share this:</h3><div class=\"sd-content\"><ul><li class=\"share-facebook\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"share-facebook sd-button share-icon\" href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/2013/12/20/what-happens-when-one-of-your-coworkers-dies/?share=facebook\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Share on Facebook\" id=\"sharing-facebook-7185\"><span>Facebook</span></a></li><li class=\"share-twitter\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"share-twitter sd-button share-icon\" href=\"https://rottenindenmark.wordpress.com/2013/12/20/what-happens-when-one-of-your-coworkers-dies/?share=twitter\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Click to share on Twitter\" id=\"sharing-twitter-7185\"><span>Twitter</span></a></li><li class=\"share-tumblr\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"share-t